82.6	Alexander_Fleming	Alexander Fleming	Sir Alexander Fleming (6 August 1881 â€“ 11 March 1955) was a Scottish biologist and pharmacologist. He wrote many articles on bacteriology, immunology, and chemotherapy. His best-known discoveries are the discovery of the enzyme lysozyme in 1923 and the antibiotic substance penicillin from the mould Penicillium notatum in 1928, for which he shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1945 with Howard Florey and Ernst Boris Chain.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f5/Alexander_Fleming_1945.jpg
